"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Psalms chapters 48–54
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-psalms-48-54.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/psalms.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/psalms.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/psalms.json (continuity)

Key Christological decisions in this range:
- Ps 48: Zion theology culminates in the heavenly Jerusalem (Heb 12:22; Rev 21:2); "the great King"
  in v2 becomes the Matthean epithet for Jerusalem (Matt 5:35) and ultimately Christ's throne city.
- Ps 49:7-9: The ransom paradox — no human can ransom another — is the negative premise resolved
  in Mark 10:45 ("the Son of Man came to give his life as a ransom for many") and 1 Pet 1:18-19
  (redeemed not with silver/gold but Christ's precious blood).
- Ps 49:15: "God will ransom my soul from Sheol; he will take me" — one of the OT's clearest
  pre-resurrectional statements; Acts 2:27/Ps 16:10 pattern.
- Ps 50: The covenant lawsuit psalm where YHWH corrects sacrificial formalism; Heb 10:5-10 fulfills
  the trajectory (Christ's body > all animal sacrifice); v21 "you thought I was like you" inverted
  in John 14:9 ("whoever has seen me has seen the Father").
- Ps 51:4: Paul quotes in Romans 3:4 to establish YHWH's righteousness in justification.
- Ps 51:10: bara' (create, same verb Gen 1:1) applied to inner transformation — 2 Cor 5:17
  (new creation) and John 3:3 (born again) as Christ-enabled fulfillments.
- Ps 51:7: Hyssop cleansing → John 19:29 (hyssop at the cross), the purification ritual enacted
  in the instrument of Christ's death.
- Ps 51:16-17: Sacrifice not wanted / broken spirit not rejected — Heb 10:5-10 quotes Ps 40:6-8
  (LXX) for the same principle; Christ's obedience replaces animal sacrifice.
- Ps 53:1-3: Quoted in Romans 3:10-12 as the universal indictment that makes Christ's atonement
  necessary — "no one does good, not even one."
- Ps 53:6: "that Israel's rescue would come out of Zion" — the hope the NT declares fulfilled
  in Christ (Luke 2:38; Rom 11:26).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: mkt-christ for Psalms 48-54 — Zion theology (Ps 48), wisdom on wealth/death with
#   ransom paradox (Ps 49), covenant lawsuit correcting formalism (Ps 50), the Miserere/
#   penitential psalm (Ps 51), contrast of wicked and righteous (Ps 52-54); key NT citations
#   throughout: Rom 3:4 (Ps 51:4), Rom 3:10-12 (Ps 53:1-3), Mark 10:45 (Ps 49:7-9).
# CHANGE? If commentary/mkt-christ/psalms.json structure changes, update load_comm/save_comm.
# VERIFY: python3 -c "import json; d=json.load(open('data/commentary/mkt-christ/psalms.json'));
#   [print(ch, len(d[ch])) for ch in ['48','49','50','51','52','53','54']]"

PSALMS = {
  "48": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: "Great is the LORD and greatly to be praised in the city of our God, on his holy mountain." The opening doxology of this Zion Psalm grounds the Lord\'s greatness in his association with the holy city. The NT carries this forward but radically transforms its geography: the true city of God is now the heavenly Jerusalem (Heb 12:22 — "you have come to Mount Zion, to the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem"), and its ultimate form is the new creation\'s holy city (Rev 21:2). The "holy mountain" that Psalm 48 celebrates is not an end in itself but a type of the permanent dwelling of God with his people that Christ\'s work establishes.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: "Mount Zion, beautiful in its height, is the joy of all the earth; on the heights of the north it rises — the city of the great King." "The great King" (<em>melek gadol</em>) — a royal epithet for YHWH that the NT reroutes through Christ. Matthew 5:35 ("Do not swear by Jerusalem, for it is the city of the great King") cites Zion theology to relativize oath-taking; the city\'s greatness is derivative of the King\'s. Revelation 21:2-3 reveals the ultimate "city of the great King" as the new Jerusalem descending from heaven — the consummation of what Psalm 48:2 typologically celebrates. "The heights of the north" (<em>ṣāfôn</em>) echoes the Canaanite cosmic mountain Zaphon, redeploying myth to affirm YHWH\'s superiority over all rival divine claims.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "Within her citadels God has shown himself to be a fortress." The divine self-disclosure as <em>misgāv</em> (high retreat, fortress) within the city\'s defenses is a revelation of divine protective character. The NT develops this: Christ himself is identified as the refuge in whom believers are secure (Heb 6:18-19; Col 3:3). The fortress-character of God revealed through the protection of Zion reaches its fullest form in the one who says "I give them eternal life, and they shall never perish; no one will snatch them out of my hand" (John 10:28).</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "For look — the kings assembled; they came against her together." The coalition of enemies who assemble against Zion is a recurring OT pattern — Sennacherib\'s coalition (Isa 36-37), the Gog and Magog scenario (Ezek 38-39), and the eschatological battle of Ps 2 ("the kings of the earth set themselves... against the LORD and against his Anointed"). Revelation 16:14-16 describes kings gathered at Armageddon; Revelation 19:19 shows the beast and the kings of the earth gathered against the rider on the white horse. The gathering against Zion always ends with divine victory, and the ultimate version is the Parousia.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "They saw it and were bewildered; they were struck with terror and fled." The enemy\'s terror at the sight of the city under divine protection anticipates the terror of unbelievers at the return of Christ: Luke 21:26 ("people will faint from fear and apprehension of what is coming on the world"); Revelation 6:15-17 (kings, generals, the mighty hiding "from the face of him who sits on the throne and from the wrath of the Lamb"). The same bewilderment and terror that scattered the enemies of Zion will accompany the final revelation of the one who is both the Lamb and the Lion.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "Trembling took hold of them there, pain like that of a woman giving birth." The birth-pang simile for eschatological crisis — travail that is severe but ends in life — is a major OT image (Isa 26:17-19; Jer 30:6-7; Mic 4:9-10) that Jesus deploys directly: "All this is the beginning of birth pains" (Matt 24:8; Mark 13:8) for the eschatological events preceding his return. 1 Thessalonians 5:3 uses the same image for the sudden onset of the Day of the Lord. The trembling of the enemies before Zion prefigures the universal crisis that accompanies the final revelation of Christ\'s victory.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "With the east wind you shatter the ships of Tarshish." Tarshish ships — the largest, most prestigious merchantmen of the ancient world, representing the peak of human commercial and maritime achievement (1 Kgs 10:22; Isa 2:16) — are shattered by a mere wind from God. Isaiah 2:12-17 develops the same image: YHWH\'s day will bring low every proud tower and ship of Tarshish. James 5:1-5 echoes the same critique of wealth that does not survive judgment. The ships of Tarshish are the OT symbol for what 1 John 2:17 calls "the world and its desires" — they pass away; the divine Word stands forever.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "As we have heard, so we have seen in the city of the LORD of hosts, in the city of our God; God establishes it forever." The correspondence of testimony and experience — what was heard in tradition matched by what was seen in history — is the pattern of faith confirmed. The NT applies this to Christ: "we are witnesses" (Acts 2:32; 3:15; 5:32; 10:39) is the apostolic testimony that what the OT promised has been seen in Jesus. Hebrews 2:3 appeals to the same principle: the salvation "announced by the Lord and confirmed to us by those who heard him." God\'s establishment of his city "forever" is the permanence of the kingdom that Christ\'s resurrection inaugurates (Dan 2:44; Rev 11:15).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: "We have meditated on your steadfast love, O God, within your temple." The contemplation of divine <em>hesed</em> (covenant love) within the sacred space — the spiritual practice of fixing attention on the faithful character of God — is what the NT calls "beholding the glory of the Lord" (2 Cor 3:18). The temple in which this meditation occurs is, in the NT, ultimately Christ\'s own body (John 2:21), and then the community of the Spirit (1 Cor 3:16; Eph 2:21). Meditating on steadfast love within the temple becomes, for believers, contemplating the love of Christ "that surpasses knowledge" (Eph 3:19) within the community he inhabits.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: "As your name reaches, O God, so does your praise — to the ends of the earth; your right hand is full of righteousness." The universality of divine praise — proportional to the reach of the divine name — is the vision that the NT\'s mission embodies: "from the rising of the sun to the place where it sets, the name of the LORD is to be praised" (Ps 113:3); "this gospel of the kingdom will be proclaimed in all the world as a testimony to all nations" (Matt 24:14). "Your right hand is full of righteousness" — Christ is seated at the right hand of the Father (Acts 2:33; Heb 1:3), and his righteous acts are what the nations will come to worship (Rev 15:4).</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme: "Let Mount Zion rejoice; let the towns of Judah be glad because of your righteous judgments." The expansion of Zion-joy to the surrounding towns and territories anticipates the spread of the gospel from Jerusalem outward (Luke 24:47; Acts 1:8: "in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth"). The "righteous judgments" that produce joy are, in the NT, the justice accomplished at the cross (Rom 3:25-26: God presented Christ as an atoning sacrifice "to demonstrate his righteousness") — the judgment that both condemns sin and acquits the believer.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme: "Walk all around Zion, circle her, count her towers." The pilgrimage practice of walking the perimeter of Jerusalem — surveying its strength and beauty for communal memory — is the OT liturgical form of what Hebrews calls "fixing our eyes on Jesus" (Heb 12:2). The "towers" to be counted are the strength of the city that belongs to YHWH. In the new Jerusalem, there are no towers to count for defensive purposes, because "the Lord God Almighty and the Lamb are its temple" (Rev 21:22) and "the glory of God is its light" (Rev 21:23). The strength of the physical city gives way to the strength of the divine presence.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme: "Mark her walls carefully, tour her citadels, that you may tell the next generation." The transmission of Zion\'s story to the next generation — the catechetical function of pilgrimage — is the pattern of the apostolic tradition. 2 Timothy 2:2: "what you have heard from me in the presence of many witnesses, entrust to faithful people who will be able to teach others also." The "walls and citadels" that are to be marked, toured, and reported are, in the NT, the acts of God in Christ: the incarnation, death, resurrection, and ascension that "we are witnesses of" (Acts 2:32) and that "we declare to you" (1 John 1:1-3).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "For this God is our God forever and ever; he will guide us until the very end (<em>al-mût</em>)." The closing declaration of the psalm — "this God is our God forever" — is the claim that YHWH is not a regional deity but the eternal God who guides beyond death itself. <em>Al-mût</em> is ambiguous: "unto death," "beyond death," or a musical term (Heb. may mean "upon death/dying"). Whichever reading, the claim that God guides through the final boundary is fulfilled in Christ: "I am the resurrection and the life. The one who believes in me will live, even though they die" (John 11:25). Hebrews 13:20-21 describes the God who guides "forever and ever" as the God of peace who raised Christ from the dead.</p>',
  },
  "49": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: Psalm 49 opens as a Wisdom Psalm addressed universally — "Hear this, all peoples! Listen, all who live in the world." The scope is deliberately universal, not limited to Israel: the question of wealth, death, and what can ransom a life is a human question, not a Jewish question. The NT\'s answer operates at the same universal scope: "God so loved the world" (John 3:16); the ransom Christ offers is for "all peoples." The opening summons anticipates the inclusive reach of the gospel to every tribe and nation (Rev 5:9).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: "the humble and the great alike, the rich and the poor together." The leveling of humanity before the wisdom teaching — all are subject to the same mortality and the same ransom problem — is a core NT principle. James 2:1-7 addresses the honor-shame partiality that favored the rich in the assembly; Luke 1:52 (the Magnificat) celebrates the reversal that exalts the humble and brings down the powerful. Before the cross, all are equal in need: "for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God" (Rom 3:23).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "My mouth will speak wisdom, and the reflection of my heart will be understanding." The wisdom spoken in this psalm is ultimately the wisdom that Christ embodies. 1 Corinthians 1:24 calls Christ "the power of God and the wisdom of God"; Colossians 2:3 says "in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge." The psalmist\'s wisdom about the limits of wealth and the irreversibility of death is a fragment of the divine wisdom that Christ fully embodies and imparts.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "I bend my ear to a proverb; I will open my riddle with the harp." The wisdom riddle (<em>hîdāh</em>) that the psalmist opens with the harp is a form of encoded truth requiring interpretation. Christ speaks in parables for similar reasons (Matt 13:11-17: "to you it has been given to know the secrets of the kingdom of heaven, but to them it has not been given"). The "riddle" that Psalm 49 opens is: can anyone ransom another from death? The answer is no — except one. That exception is the hidden answer that the psalm does not fully name but that the NT reveals.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "Why should I be afraid in evil days, when the guilt of my accusers closes in around me?" The freedom from fear in days of evil — confidence in the face of accusation — is a theme the NT grounds in Christ. Romans 8:1 ("there is now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus") and Romans 8:33-34 ("who will bring any charge against those whom God has chosen?... who is the one who condemns? No one. Christ Jesus... is at the right hand of God and is also interceding for us") are the NT\'s answer to the fear of accusation. The courage of v5 is the courage of those who know their ransom has been paid.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "those who trust in their wealth and boast of their great riches" — the misplaced confidence in material wealth as the ultimate security. The NT addresses this repeatedly: Luke 12:15-21 (the rich fool whose soul is required that night); Luke 18:24-25 (how hard it is for the rich to enter the kingdom of God); 1 Timothy 6:17 ("command those who are rich in this present world not to be arrogant nor to put their hope in wealth"). The trust-in-wealth that Psalm 49 treats as a moral failure is the misorientation that Christ\'s teaching consistently redirects toward trust in God.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct anticipation: "truly no one can ransom another person, or give God a payment for their life." The ransom impossibility at the human level — the absolute prohibition on one person substituting for another\'s death before God — is the negative premise that the gospel\'s good news resolves. Mark 10:45: "the Son of Man did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many." The word "ransom" (<em>lytron</em>) is taken directly from the Levitical ransom-payment vocabulary that Ps 49:7 invokes. What no human can do, Christ does as the God-man: pay the price that exceeds all human wealth.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct anticipation: "for the price of their life is too high; the payment would never be enough." The impossibility of the ransom is not a technical problem but an ontological one: the value of a human life before God is infinite, which means no finite payment suffices. 1 Peter 1:18-19: "you were redeemed not with perishable things such as silver or gold... but with the precious blood of Christ, a lamb without blemish or defect." The blood of Christ is the only non-perishable payment that matches the infinite cost that Psalm 49:8 declares impossible for humans to meet.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct anticipation: "no sum could keep him alive forever, safe from seeing Sheol." The impossibility of purchasing immortality through wealth — no human financial transaction can defeat death — establishes the context for the gospel\'s offer. Hebrews 2:14-15: "since the children have flesh and blood, he too shared in their humanity so that by his death he might break the power of him who holds the power of death — that is, the devil — and free those who all their lives were held in slavery by their fear of death." The life that no sum can purchase is the life Christ freely gives: "the wages of sin is death, but the gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord" (Rom 6:23).</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: "He sees that even the wise die — the fool and the senseless alike perish and leave their wealth behind for others." The death of the wise alongside the foolish establishes death\'s universality — it does not respect the human value of wisdom any more than wealth. 1 Corinthians 15:21-22: "since death came through a man, the resurrection of the dead comes also through a man. For as in Adam all die, so in Christ all will be made alive." The death of the wise and foolish alike, and the inability to carry wealth beyond death, are the anthropological conditions that make Christ\'s resurrection the only genuine answer.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme: "In their hearts they imagined their homes would last forever, their estates from generation to generation; they stamped their names on their lands." The legacy-building instinct — wanting to be remembered through property and lineage — is the substitute for the eternity that wealth cannot purchase. Jesus directly addresses this: Luke 12:19-20 (the rich man who says "I\'ll say to myself, \'You have plenty of grain laid up for many years... But God said to him, \'You fool! This very night your life will be demanded from you\'"). The names stamped on lands do not survive into eternity; only names written in the Lamb\'s book of life do (Rev 21:27).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme: "Man in all his honor will not last; he is like the animals that die." The equation of honored humanity with animals in their mortality — the denial that social status changes the biological reality of death — is the OT\'s bluntest statement of creaturely limitation. Romans 5:12 generalizes it theologically: "death spread to all people, because all sinned." Christ is the one exception: as fully human and thus sharing the same creaturely mortality (Heb 2:14), he died — but as the source of life, he rose (John 5:26: "as the Father has life in himself, so he has granted the Son also to have life in himself").</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme: "This is the fate of those who are confident in themselves, and after them people applaud their talk." Self-confidence — <em>kesel</em> (folly, self-trust) — as the defining characteristic of those who pursue wealth without reckoning with death. The applause of those who follow them confirms their folly rather than refuting it. James 4:13-14 targets the same overconfidence: "Now listen, you who say, \'Today or tomorrow we will go to this or that city, spend a year there....\' Why, you do not even know what will happen tomorrow." The antidote is not pessimism but Christ-centered realism: "What is your life? You are a mist... Instead, you ought to say, \'If it is the Lord\'s will, we will live and do this or that.\'"</p>',
    "14": '<p>A type: "Like sheep they are headed for Sheol; Death will be their shepherd, and the upright will have dominion over them in the morning." The grim inversion — Death as shepherd, driving the flocks of the self-confident into <em>Sheol</em> — is the anti-image of Christ as the Good Shepherd. John 10:11 ("I am the good shepherd; the good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep") and Revelation 7:17 ("the Lamb at the center of the throne will be their shepherd; he will lead them to springs of living water") are the NT\'s positive realization of the shepherd figure. The upright who "have dominion in the morning" (<em>labbōqer</em>) points forward to resurrection morning, when those ransomed by Christ\'s blood exercise the dominion that Adam forfeited (Rev 5:10: "a kingdom and priests... and they will reign").</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct anticipation: "But God will ransom my soul from the grip of Sheol; for he will take me (<em>yiqqāhēnî</em>)." This verse is one of the OT\'s clearest pre-resurrectional affirmations: the righteous individual confesses that God will ransom him from Sheol\'s grip and "take him" — the same rare verb used of Enoch\'s translation (Gen 5:24) and Elijah\'s ascension (2 Kgs 2:1, 3, 5, 9, 10). Peter\'s Pentecost sermon (Acts 2:27-31) applies the same logic to Christ: God did not abandon him to Sheol; his soul was not left in the realm of the dead. The ransoming of Psalm 49:15 is accomplished through the cross (the payment) and confirmed by the resurrection (the release from Sheol\'s grip).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme: "Do not be frightened when someone becomes rich, when the splendor of their household grows." The command not to fear wealth\'s appearance — not to measure reality by the temporary prosperity of the wicked — is the fear-not of the wisdom tradition that the NT deepens. Matthew 6:19-20 ("Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth... but store up treasures in heaven") and Hebrews 13:5 ("Keep your lives free from the love of money and be content with what you have, because God has said, \'Never will I leave you; never will I forsake you\'") provide the christological and pneumatological grounding for the freedom from fear that v16 commands.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A theme: "for when they die they take nothing with them; their glory will not follow them down." The impossibility of post-mortem wealth transfer is the axiom of all wisdom teaching on possessions. 1 Timothy 6:7 quotes it almost exactly: "we brought nothing into the world, and we can take nothing out of it." The only thing that follows a person beyond death is what was done in the body (2 Cor 5:10: "we must all appear before the judgment seat of Christ, so that each of us may receive what is due us for the things done while in the body"). Christ\'s resurrection establishes what does survive death — not wealth but the deeds done in faith (Rev 14:13: "their deeds will follow them").</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: "Though in their lifetime they counted themselves fortunate — and people praised them for prospering." The social feedback loop of prosperity — the wealthy receiving praise that reinforces their self-assessment — is what Luke 6:26 warns about: "Woe to you when everyone speaks well of you, for that is how their ancestors treated the false prophets." The prosperity that generates social approval is not the measure of divine favor. Christ consistently inverts the prosperity-as-blessing equation: "Blessed are you who are poor, for yours is the kingdom of God" (Luke 6:20).</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: "but they will go to join their ancestors and never again see the light." The finality of death for those who trusted in wealth — joining the ancestors in the dark — is the grim endpoint of the psalm\'s relentless logic. John 8:12 contains Christ\'s direct answer: "I am the light of the world. Whoever follows me will never walk in darkness but will have the light of life." The darkness of Sheol that awaits the wealthy fool is precisely what Christ as "the light of the world" and "the resurrection and the life" (John 11:25) overcomes for those who trust not in wealth but in him.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A theme: "Man in all his honor, but without understanding, is like the animals that die." The refrain (nearly identical to v12) closes the psalm with its central paradox: human honor without wisdom is indistinguishable from animal existence in its outcome. Proverbs 2:6 ("for the LORD gives wisdom; from his mouth come knowledge and understanding") and 1 Corinthians 1:30 ("Christ Jesus, who has become for us wisdom from God — that is, our righteousness, holiness and redemption") define the "understanding" that Psalm 49:20 says is lacking. Christ is the wisdom that distinguishes the genuinely honored human from the animal; without him, even the most socially prestigious life ends at the same grave.</p>',
  },
  "50": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "The Mighty One, God, the LORD, speaks and summons the earth from east to west." The triple divine name — <em>El Elohim YHWH</em> — opens this covenant lawsuit psalm with a theophanic summons of universal scope. The divine judge who "speaks and summons the earth" is the same judge who will summon all nations at the final judgment. John 5:22-23 transfers this judicial authority to Christ: "the Father judges no one, but has entrusted all judgment to the Son, that all may honor the Son just as they honor the Father." The God who summons the earth in Ps 50:1 summons it through the Son.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "Out of Zion, perfect in beauty, God blazes out." The theophanic blazing of God from Zion — the divine glory manifesting from the covenant city — is the language of theophany that the NT applies to the Parousia. 2 Thessalonians 1:7-8: Christ will be "revealed from heaven in blazing fire with his powerful angels." The "perfect in beauty" of Zion prefigures the "glorious appearing of our great God and Savior, Jesus Christ" (Titus 2:13). The divine blazing from Zion is ultimately the blazing of the Son of God in his eschatological self-revelation.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "Our God comes and will not stay silent; fire devours before him, and a fierce storm rages around him." The advent of the divine judge — coming, not silent, accompanied by fire and storm — is the eschatological arrival pattern. Hebrews 12:29 ("our God is a consuming fire") and 1 Thessalonians 4:16 ("the Lord himself will come down from heaven, with a loud command, with the voice of the archangel and with the trumpet call of God") develop this arrival pattern for the return of Christ. The God who will not stay silent is the Word made flesh who spoke creation into existence and who will speak the final judgment.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "He calls out to the heavens above and to the earth, to judge his people." The judicial summons of heaven and earth as witnesses — the covenant lawsuit structure (<em>rîv</em>) where creation witnesses the case against Israel — is a prophetic form (Isa 1:2; Mic 6:1-2). Christ is both the judge of v4 and, in his earthly life, the one judged on behalf of his people: "God made him who had no sin to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God" (2 Cor 5:21). The judgment against God\'s people that Ps 50 pronounces was absorbed by Christ at the cross.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "Bring together my faithful people, those who sealed covenant with me by sacrifice." The gathering of the covenant community — the <em>hasidim</em> (faithful/devout ones) who formalized the covenant through sacrifice — is the positive counterpart to the judgment on formalism in the psalm. Hebrews 9:15: "Christ is the mediator of a new covenant, that those who are called may receive the promised eternal inheritance — now that he has died as a ransom to set them free from the sins committed under the first covenant." The "sealing by sacrifice" of the old covenant (Exod 24:8) is the pattern fulfilled in Christ\'s blood of the new covenant (Matt 26:28; Heb 9:20).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "The heavens declare his righteousness, for God himself is the judge." Creation\'s testimony to divine righteousness is the cosmological grounding of the psalm\'s covenant lawsuit. Romans 1:18-20 appeals to the same created witness: "what may be known about God is plain... because God has made it plain... his eternal power and divine nature." But the fullest declaration of divine righteousness is not cosmological but Christological: "God presented Christ as a sacrifice of atonement... to demonstrate his righteousness" (Rom 3:25-26). The heavens that declare YHWH\'s righteousness in Ps 50:6 are declaring the righteousness of the judge who is also the atoning sacrifice.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "\'Listen, my people, and I will speak; I will testify against you, O Israel. I am God, your God.\'" The divine self-identification ("I am God, your God") within the covenant lawsuit is the covenant formula of Sinai (Exod 20:2 — "I am the LORD your God"). The one who speaks here is the one who gave the Torah at Sinai — and in the NT, this divine speaker is identified with Christ: John 8:58 ("before Abraham was born, I am!"); 1 Corinthians 10:4 ("the spiritual rock that accompanied them... was Christ"). The "I am God, your God" of Ps 50:7 is the same divine identity that Christ claims throughout John\'s Gospel in the <em>ego eimi</em> ("I am") declarations.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: "\'My rebuke is not over your sacrifices; your burnt offerings are always before me.\'" YHWH\'s rebuke is not about the quantity of sacrifice — Israel has been offering. The problem is the misunderstanding of what sacrifice does: it is not a mechanism for feeding or obligating God. Hebrews 10:1 makes the same point about Levitical sacrifice: "the law is only a shadow of the good things that are coming — not the realities themselves. For this reason it can never, by the same sacrifices repeated endlessly year after year, make perfect those who draw near to worship." The sacrificial system was not the endpoint but the pointing-toward of the one sacrifice that does accomplish what all the burnt offerings could not.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: "\'I do not need a bull from your household or goats from your pens.\'" The divine independence from human food-provision — YHWH does not require feeding like the gods of surrounding nations — demolishes the ANE transactional sacrificial model. Psalm 50\'s critique of the "feeding the gods" conception is the same critique that Acts 17:25 voices in Paul\'s Areopagus speech: "he is not served by human hands, as if he needed anything, because he himself gives everyone life and breath and everything else." The God who does not need to be fed is the God who instead feeds his people — most fully in Christ, the bread of life (John 6:35).</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "\'Every animal of the forest is mine — the cattle on a thousand hills.\'" Divine ownership of all creation — the total sovereign possession that makes human sacrifice-offering not a gift but a return of what was already his. This is the theological basis for Paul\'s statement that "the earth is the Lord\'s, and everything in it" (1 Cor 10:26, citing Ps 24:1). In Christ, the creator\'s ownership is disclosed in its fullest form: "in him all things were created... and in him all things hold together" (Col 1:16-17). The God who owns all the cattle cannot be bribed or compensated; he can only be worshiped.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "\'I know every bird in the hills; everything that moves in the open fields is mine.\'" Divine omniscience over all creatures — the total knowledge of the creator who tracks every sparrow. Matthew 10:29-31 develops exactly this claim through Christ: "Are not two sparrows sold for a penny? Yet not one of them will fall to the ground outside your Father\'s care. And even the very hairs of your head are all numbered." The God who knows every bird in Psalm 50:11 is the Father who watches the sparrow in Matthew 10 — and his care for birds is the ground for his far greater care for humans made in his image.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "\'If I were hungry, I would not come to you — the world and everything in it is mine.\'" The divine independence from creaturely provision — YHWH owns the world — is both a refutation of transactional religion and a revelation of the Creator\'s self-sufficiency. John 1:3 applies this ownership to the pre-incarnate Word: "through him all things were made; without him nothing was made that has been made." The God who needs nothing from humans is the same God who nonetheless became human in Christ — not because he needed to but because we needed him. Grace, not necessity, drives the incarnation.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme: "\'Do I eat bull meat? Do I drink the blood of goats?\'" The rhetorical reductio of sacrificial misunderstanding — YHWH eating and drinking the animal offerings — is the clearest OT demolition of the ANE gods-need-food conception. This sets up the NT\'s paradox: in the Eucharist, the relationship is inverted — humans eat and drink (bread and wine as body and blood of Christ, John 6:53-56), not as feeding God but as receiving what God provides. The Lord\'s Supper is the antithesis of v13: not humans feeding YHWH animal blood, but Christ offering himself as the food and drink that gives eternal life.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A theme: "\'Bring God a thank-offering as your sacrifice, and keep your vows to the Most High.\'" The redirection from animal sacrifice to <em>todah</em> (thank-offering, praise) is the psalm\'s key constructive move: the sacrifice God wants is gratitude and covenant faithfulness, not animal meat. Hebrews 13:15-16 applies this to the post-Christ community: "through Jesus, therefore, let us continually offer to God a sacrifice of praise — the fruit of lips that openly profess his name. And do not forget to do good and to share with others, for with such sacrifices God is pleased." The thank-offering of Psalm 50:14 is the NT\'s sacrificial practice — offered "through Jesus."</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "\'Call on me when trouble comes; I will rescue you, and you will honor me.\'" The divine invitation — call, receive rescue, honor — is the covenantal pattern of prayer. Romans 10:12-13 applies this pattern to Christ: "the same Lord is Lord of all and richly blesses all who call on him, for, \'Everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved.\'" (citing Joel 2:32). The "name of the LORD" on whom all may call in v15 is the name that is "above every name" given to Christ (Phil 2:9). The rescue promised in Ps 50:15 is the salvation offered in the name of Jesus Christ.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme: "But to the wicked, God says: \'What right do you have to quote my laws, or to take my covenant on your lips?\'" The critique of selective covenant-membership — claiming the covenant verbally while violating it practically — is what Jesus addresses throughout the Sermon on the Mount and in his critique of the Pharisees (Matt 23:3: "do as they say, but not as they do"). Romans 2:17-24 makes the same argument that Psalm 50:16-21 makes: "you rely on the law and boast in God... you who preach against stealing, do you steal?" The lip-covenant that the heart denies is the religious failure that Christ\'s teaching consistently exposes.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A theme: "\'You despise correction and fling my words aside.\'" The contempt for divine discipline (<em>mûsār</em>) — the educational instruction that YHWH uses to shape covenant character — is what Hebrews 12:5-6 identifies as a spiritual failure: "do not make light of the Lord\'s discipline... because the Lord disciplines the one he loves." Christ is both the source of this discipline (Heb 12:7-11) and its model: "although he was a son, he learned obedience from what he suffered" (Heb 5:8). The word-flinging of Ps 50:17 is the opposite of the obedience that Christ embodied.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: "\'When you see a thief you go along with him, and you make yourself at home with adulterers.\'" Social complicity in sin — the tacit endorsement of others\' violations — is what Romans 1:32 identifies as the depth of moral corruption: "although they know God\'s righteous decree that those who do such things deserve death, they not only continue to do these very things but also approve of those who practice them." Christ\'s holiness is the antithesis: he ate with sinners (which the Pharisees attacked) but not to endorse their sin — rather to call them to repentance (Luke 5:31-32). Associating with sinners without approving their sin is the gospel pattern Christ modeled.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: "\'You let your mouth run loose into evil, and your tongue is busy weaving lies.\'" The unbridled tongue — speech as the avenue for evil rather than blessing — is the failure that James 3:1-12 addresses at length: "the tongue is a fire, a world of evil among the parts of the body." Christ is the Word who embodies perfect speech: "no deceit was found in his mouth" (1 Pet 2:22, citing Isa 53:9); "gracious words came from his lips" (Luke 4:22). The contrast between the lying tongue of Ps 50:19 and the truthful Word made flesh is total.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A theme: "\'You sit and talk against your own brother; you slander your mother\'s son.\'" Covenantal betrayal within the family — the slander of one\'s kin — is the social violation that Matthew 18:15-17 addresses with the community-discipline procedure. But the most extreme instance of brother-against-brother in the biblical narrative is the betrayal of Jesus by Judas (John 13:18, citing Ps 41:9: "even my close friend, whom I trusted... has lifted up his heel against me"). The slander and betrayal of v20 find their darkest expression in the passion narrative.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "\'You did all these things, and I said nothing. You concluded I must be just like you. But now I rebuke you and lay everything out before you.\'" The dangerous misreading of divine patience as divine approval — "God must be like me" — is the theological error that the cross exposes definitively. Romans 2:4-5: "do you presume on the riches of his kindness, forbearance and patience, not knowing that God\'s kindness is intended to lead you to repentance? But because of your stubbornness... you are storing up wrath." John 14:9 inverts the error: "whoever has seen me has seen the Father." The cross is the definitive rebuttal of "I thought God was like me" — he is holy, and the cost of holiness meeting sin was borne by his Son.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme: "\'Take this seriously, you who have forgotten God, or I will tear you apart, and no one will rescue you.\'" The warning of unrescuable divine judgment against those who forget God is the Old Covenant\'s starkest ultimatum. Luke 13:3, 5 (Jesus: "unless you repent, you too will all perish") carries the same urgency. Hebrews 2:3 makes the logic of urgency explicit in Christ: "how shall we escape if we ignore so great a salvation?" The one who "will tear apart" the unrepentant in Ps 50:22 is the same one who says in Matt 10:28: "be afraid of the One who can destroy both soul and body in hell."</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "\'Whoever brings thanksgiving as their sacrifice glorifies me; to the one who walks a right path I will show the salvation of God.\'" The psalm closes with its constructive vision: praise-as-sacrifice and covenant-walking as the path to divine salvation (<em>yēša\'</em>). The Hebrew <em>yēša\'</em> (salvation) is the root from which the name Yēšûaʿ (Jesus) derives. "I will show them the salvation of God" — in Christ, God has not merely shown salvation but embodied it. The <em>todah</em> sacrifice that glorifies God in v23 is what the NT community offers "through Jesus" (Heb 13:15), the one whose name means "YHWH saves."</p>',
  },
  "51": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: "Have mercy on me, O God, according to your steadfast love; according to your abundant compassion wipe out my transgressions." The superscription grounds this psalm in David\'s confession after Nathan\'s confrontation (2 Sam 12:1-14) — the paradigmatic penitential prayer. The petition for mercy (<em>hānan</em>) and covenant love (<em>hesed</em>) is the fundamental prayer structure the NT assumes. Luke 18:13 (the tax collector: "God, have mercy on me, a sinner") is built on the same cry. Christ is the one through whom the mercy of Psalm 51:1 is channeled: Hebrews 4:16 ("receive mercy and find grace to help us in our time of need") grounds this in our access to the throne of grace through the great high priest.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: "Scrub away my guilt completely, and purify me from my sin." The plea for comprehensive moral cleansing uses two washing metaphors: <em>kābas</em> (the vigorous scrubbing of soiled garments) and <em>ṭāhēr</em> (ritual purification). 1 John 1:7: "the blood of Jesus, his Son, purifies us from all sin" — the purification that Levitical ritual could only symbolize, Christ accomplishes definitively. Hebrews 10:22: "let us draw near to God with a sincere heart and with the full assurance that faith brings, having our hearts sprinkled to cleanse us from a guilty conscience." The scrubbing and purifying of Ps 51:2 is what Christ\'s blood accomplishes for the conscience.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "For I know my rebellions, and my sin is before me at every moment." The acknowledged omnipresence of sin — sin that cannot be ignored or forgotten — is the spiritual condition that precedes and enables genuine repentance. Romans 7:24 (Paul: "What a wretched man I am! Who will rescue me from this body that is subject to death?") expresses the same relentless awareness of moral failure. The answer in Romans 7:25 is "Jesus Christ our Lord." The sin that is "before me at every moment" in Ps 51:3 drives the penitent to the one who alone can remove it from God\'s sight permanently (Heb 10:17: "their sins and lawless acts I will remember no more").</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct citation: "Against you — you alone — have I sinned and done what is evil in your sight, so that you are proved right when you speak and blameless when you judge." Paul quotes the last clause in Romans 3:4 as proof that God is righteous in his justifying judgment: "let God be true, and every human being a liar. As it is written: \'So that you may be proved right when you speak and prevail when you judge.\'" The theological move is striking: David\'s confession of sin (which vindicates God\'s judgment against him) becomes Paul\'s proof that God\'s justifying verdict in Christ is righteous. The God proved right in judging David is proved right in justifying the sinner through Christ\'s atoning death.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "Surely I was brought forth into guilt, and in sin my mother conceived me." The ontological depth of sin — not merely acts but the condition of existence from conception — is the anthropological claim behind Paul\'s doctrine of original sin (Rom 5:12-14). This is not a statement about the sinfulness of sexual union (the Fathers sometimes misread it thus) but about the solidarity of the human race in Adam\'s fallen condition. The need for new birth (John 3:3-8), new creation (2 Cor 5:17), and the second Adam (1 Cor 15:45-49) are all responses to the condition that Psalm 51:5 names: sin at the level of origin, not merely behavior.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "You desire truth deep inside a person; in the hidden place you are teaching me wisdom." The divine desire for inner truth — the integrity of <em>tûmāh</em> (truth/sincerity) in the hidden depths (<em>ṭûhôt</em>) of the person — is what Christ identifies as the heart of the commandment (Matt 5:8: "blessed are the pure in heart, for they will see God"; Matt 5:28: inward desire = the act). John 4:23-24 ("God is spirit, and his worshipers must worship in the Spirit and in truth") develops the "inner truth" of v6 into the pneumatological reality that Christ enables. The wisdom taught "in the hidden place" is the wisdom of the Spirit: 1 Cor 2:10 ("the Spirit searches all things, even the deep things of God").</p>',
    "7": '<p>A shadow: "Cleanse me with hyssop, and I will be clean; wash me, and I will be whiter than snow." Hyssop (<em>ēzôv</em>) is the ritual instrument of purification in the Mosaic law — used to apply blood in the Passover (Exod 12:22), in the cleansing of skin disease (Lev 14:4, 6, 51), and in the red heifer purification (Num 19:6, 18). At the crucifixion, hyssop is the instrument used to offer Jesus the sour wine (John 19:29). The hyssop of Psalm 51:7 — the instrument of ritual cleansing — becomes at Golgotha the instrument through which the ultimate cleansing sacrifice is administered. The ritual shadow of purification-by-hyssop is enacted in reverse at the cross.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: "Let me hear the sounds of joy and gladness; let the bones you have crushed be glad." The crushed bones as the somatic image of guilt under divine judgment — and the hope for their restoration to joy — is a pattern the resurrection fulfills. Hebrews 12:11: "no discipline seems pleasant at the time, but painful; later on, however, it produces a harvest of righteousness and peace for those who have been trained by it." The bones crushed by divine discipline are healed not by the removal of the discipline but by its completion in Christ\'s suffering (1 Pet 4:1: "since Christ suffered in his body, arm yourselves with the same attitude").</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: "Look away from my sins; wipe out all my guilt." The plea for divine non-seeing of sin — the averting of the divine face from the record of transgression — is what atonement accomplishes. Hebrews 10:17 (citing Jer 31:34): "their sins and lawless acts I will remember no more." The mechanism of this divine non-seeing is Christ\'s sacrifice: "God presented Christ as a sacrifice of atonement... He did this to demonstrate his righteousness, because in his forbearance he had left the sins committed beforehand unpunished" (Rom 3:25). The wiping out of guilt in Ps 51:9 is the "blotting out" (Col 2:14: "having canceled the charge of our legal indebtedness... he took it away, nailing it to the cross").</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct anticipation: "Create a pure heart in me, O God, and renew a steadfast spirit within me." The verb <em>bārā\'</em> (create) is used here — the same word used only for divine creative action in the OT (Gen 1:1, 21, 27; 2:3, 4; Isa 40:26, 28; 45:12, 18). David is not asking for moral improvement but for a new creation. 2 Corinthians 5:17: "if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come: the old has gone, the new is here!" John 3:3-8 (born again from above by the Spirit) and Ezekiel 36:26 ("I will give you a new heart and put a new spirit in you") are the Christological and pneumatological fulfillments of this petition. The new creation of v10 is what Christ enables through the Spirit.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct anticipation: "Do not banish me from your presence; do not take your Holy Spirit from me." The fear of the loss of the Holy Spirit — <em>ruah qodshekha</em> (your Holy Spirit) — reflects the OT\'s conditional pneumatology: the Spirit could be withdrawn from Saul (1 Sam 16:14). Christ\'s promise in John 14:16-17 is the definitive answer to this fear: "I will ask the Father, and he will give you another advocate to help you and be with you forever — the Spirit of truth." The Spirit given through Christ is not taken away; the fear of Psalm 51:11 is met by the permanence of the Spirit\'s indwelling in the new covenant community.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme: "Give back to me the joy of your rescue, and sustain me with a generous, willing spirit." The "joy of rescue" — the gladness that belongs to the one who has experienced divine salvation — is what Christ restores to those who come to him. John 15:11: "I have told you this so that my joy may be in you and that your joy may be complete." The "willing spirit" (<em>nādîvāh</em> — generous, noble, freely-giving) that is asked as a sustaining gift is the Spirit that Christ pours out on those who believe (Acts 2:17-18: "I will pour out my Spirit on all people"). The rescue-joy and the willing spirit are both gifts of the new covenant through Christ.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme: "Then I will show other rebels your ways, and sinners will come back to you." The missional consequence of personal restoration — the forgiven one becoming the instrument of others\' repentance — is the pattern of the apostolic testimony. Peter\'s restoration after his denials (John 21:15-19) leads directly to his Pentecost proclamation (Acts 2:14-41). Paul\'s pre-Christian violence against the church did not disqualify him; his testimony became a means of others\' conversion (1 Tim 1:15-16). The "showing of rebels God\'s ways" in Ps 51:13 is the evangelistic fruit that genuine repentance and restoration produce.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A theme: "Rescue me from the guilt of bloodshed, O God — God of my salvation — and my tongue will ring out your righteousness." The plea for rescue from blood-guilt (<em>dāmîm</em>) — the most serious form of moral pollution in the OT (Num 35; 2 Sam 12) — points to the ultimate blood-guilt: the crucifixion itself, in which innocent blood was shed. Acts 5:28 (the Sanhedrin: "you have filled Jerusalem with your teaching and are determined to make us guilty of this man\'s blood") acknowledges the blood-guilt of the crucifixion. Christ\'s blood, paradoxically, "speaks a better word than the blood of Abel" (Heb 12:24) — not crying out for vengeance but for forgiveness of the very blood-guilt it creates.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A theme: "O Lord, open my lips, and my mouth will declare your praise." The request for divinely-opened lips — the acknowledgment that even praise requires divine enabling — is the posture of the NT community at prayer. Acts 2:4: "all of them were filled with the Holy Spirit and began to speak in other tongues as the Spirit enabled them." Ephesians 6:19: "pray also for me, that whenever I speak, words may be given me so that I will fearlessly make known the mystery of the gospel." The lips that God opens declare his praise — and the ultimate praise is the proclamation of Christ crucified and risen, which only the Spirit enables (1 Cor 12:3).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct anticipation: "You do not want sacrifice — otherwise I would bring it; you take no delight in burnt offerings." The prophetic principle that sacrifice is not YHWH\'s primary desire (cf. 1 Sam 15:22; Isa 1:11-13; Hos 6:6; Mic 6:6-8) is the OT critique of formalism that the NT fulfills. Hebrews 10:5-9 quotes Psalm 40:6-8 (LXX: "sacrifice and offering you did not desire... then I said, \'Here I am — it is written about me in the scroll — I have come to do your will, my God\'") and applies it to Christ: "he sets aside the first [the sacrificial system] to establish the second [his obedience]." The sacrifice God does not want (animal offerings) gives way to the sacrifice he does: Christ\'s body.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct anticipation: "What God wants as sacrifice is a broken spirit; a broken and crushed heart, O God, you will not reject." The theology of the broken spirit as the acceptable sacrifice — replacing animal offerings with the moral and spiritual self — is fulfilled in Christ in two ways: (1) Christ himself was "broken" in the passion (Isa 53:10: "it pleased the LORD to crush him"), his spirit the ultimate broken offering; and (2) the community he forms is invited to bring broken hearts as worship. Romans 12:1: "offer your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy and pleasing to God — this is your true and proper worship." The broken spirit that God will not reject is the heart of NT sacrificial theology.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: "In your favor, do good to Zion; build up the walls of Jerusalem." The psalm\'s closing intercession for the restoration of Jerusalem — the communal vision after the individual\'s personal restoration — reflects the theology that the individual\'s righteousness is connected to the community\'s flourishing. In the NT, the "building up" that matters is the church: Ephesians 4:12 ("for the equipping of his people for works of service, so that the body of Christ may be built up") and 1 Peter 2:5 ("you also, like living stones, are being built into a spiritual house"). Christ builds his church (Matt 16:18), the new Jerusalem, as the restoration of what Israel\'s sin had broken.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: "Then you will be pleased with right sacrifices, with burnt offerings and whole offerings; then bulls will go up on your altar." The closing verse restores sacrificial practice to its proper place — not replaced by repentance but re-grounded in it. This is not a contradiction of v16-17 but its fulfillment: sacrifice offered from a broken and contrite heart is the sacrifice God accepts. Hebrews 9:14: "how much more will the blood of Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered himself unblemished to God, cleanse our consciences from acts that lead to death, so that we may serve the living God!" The "right sacrifice" of Ps 51:19 is Christ\'s self-offering from a perfect, unbroken will — the one sacrifice that makes all subsequent offerings of praise and service acceptable.</p>',
  },
  "52": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: "Why do you boast in evil, O mighty man? The steadfast love of God endures all day." The contrast of human wickedness and enduring divine <em>hesed</em> — the boastful evil of the "mighty man" set against the permanence of covenant love — is the psalm\'s structural irony. Romans 3:27: "where then is boasting? It is excluded." The boasting in human power that Psalm 52:1 ridicules is the same boasting that Paul says the cross eliminates: 1 Corinthians 1:29 ("so that no one may boast before him"). The "mighty man" who boasts in evil is the antithesis of Christ, who "being in very nature God, did not consider equality with God something to be used to his own advantage" (Phil 2:6).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: "Your tongue plots harm, sharp as a razor blade — you craftsman of deceit." The tongue as the weapon of the wicked — the razor-sharp, craft-worked deceit — is the failure that James 3:6 describes: "the tongue also is a fire, a world of evil among the parts of the body." The tongue of the "Doeg figure" (the informant who betrayed the priests of Nob, 1 Sam 22) is the tongue of all whose words destroy rather than build. Christ, by contrast, is the Word made flesh (John 1:14) — the divine speech whose every word gives life rather than death (John 6:63: "the words I have spoken to you — they are full of the Spirit and life").</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "You love evil rather than good, and lies rather than truth." The moral inversion — the preference for evil over good, lies over truth — is what John 8:44 attributes to the devil: "he was a murderer from the beginning, not holding to the truth, for there is no truth in him. When he lies, he speaks his native language, for he is a liar and the father of lies." Those who follow the pattern of Doeg/Ps 52:3 participate in the devil\'s nature rather than Christ\'s: "I am the way and the truth and the life" (John 14:6). The love of lies over truth is the opposite of the one who is himself the truth.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "You love every word that destroys, you treacherous tongue." The destructive tongue — words as weapons rather than life-givers — is the pattern that Proverbs consistently contrasts with wisdom: "the mouth of the righteous is a fountain of life, but the mouth of the wicked conceals violence" (Prov 10:11). At Jesus\'s trial, false witnesses loved "words that destroy" (Mark 14:56-59: "many bore false witness against him — but their statements did not agree"). Christ endured the destroying words of false accusation without retaliation, "entrusting himself to him who judges justly" (1 Pet 2:23).</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "But God will pull you down permanently; he will grab and rip you from your home; he will tear you out of the land of the living." The eschatological reversal of the wicked\'s apparent security — torn from the land of the living permanently — is the covenant consequence that the NT presents as eschatological judgment. Matthew 25:41 ("depart from me, you who are cursed, into the eternal fire prepared for the devil and his angels"); Revelation 20:15 ("anyone whose name was not found written in the book of life was thrown into the lake of fire"). The tearing down of the wicked in Psalm 52:5 is the eschatological judgment that Christ will execute as the enthroned judge (Acts 17:31).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "The righteous will see and be filled with awe, and they will laugh." The awe and laughter of the righteous at divine judgment — the vindication that the suffering righteous experience when divine justice is enacted — is the pattern of the eschatological reversal. Revelation 19:1-4 describes the heavenly multitude\'s worship at the fall of Babylon ("Hallelujah! The Lord our God, the Almighty, reigns"). Luke 6:21 (Jesus: "blessed are you who weep now, for you will laugh") promises the laughter of eschatological vindication to those who mourn under the wicked\'s power. The righteous who fill with awe in Ps 52:6 are those whose faith has persisted through persecution.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "\'Here is the man who would not take refuge in God, but relied on his great wealth and found his strength in destruction.\'" The epitaph of the wicked — the negative inscription over a life built on the wrong foundation — is the warning of Jesus\'s parable of the two foundations (Matt 7:24-27). The man who builds on sand ("wealth and destruction") instead of the rock (Christ\'s words) comes to ruin when the storm comes. The "refuge in God" that the wicked of Ps 52 spurned is the refuge in Christ that the NT consistently identifies as the only stable foundation: "whoever trusts in him will never be put to shame" (Rom 10:11).</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: "But I am like a flourishing olive tree in the house of God; I trust in God\'s steadfast love forever and ever." The olive tree as the image of the righteous person rooted in YHWH\'s house — flourishing, fruitful, enduring — is the OT\'s horticultural image of covenant blessing (Ps 1:3; Jer 11:16). John 15:1-5: "I am the true vine, and my Father is the gardener... you are the branches. If you remain in me and I in you, you will bear much fruit." Christ is the true vine/tree in whom the believer is rooted; the flourishing olive tree of Ps 52:8 is the image fulfilled in those who abide in Christ, drawing life from his life.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme: "I will give you thanks forever, because of what you have done; I will hope in your name, for it is good, before your faithful people." The eternal thanksgiving grounded in divine action — "because of what you have done" — is the posture of the redeemed community. Revelation 11:17: "we give thanks to you, Lord God Almighty, the One who is and who was, because you have taken your great power and have begun to reign." The hope in the divine "name" that is "good" is the hope in the name of Jesus that is "above every name" (Phil 2:9-10) — the Name that is the ground of the eternal thanksgiving that Psalm 52:9 commits to.</p>',
  },
  "53": {
    "1": '<p>A direct citation: "The fool has said in his heart, \'There is no God.\' They are corrupt; they have done abominable deeds; there is no one who does good." Romans 3:10-12 quotes this verse (near-verbatim from LXX Ps 13/53, a near-duplicate of Ps 14) as part of the catena of OT texts proving universal human sinfulness: "There is no one righteous, not even one; there is no one who understands; there is no one who seeks God. All have turned away, they have together become worthless; there is no one who does good, not even one." The universal indictment of Psalm 53:1 is the theological precondition for Christ\'s universal atonement: "since all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God, they are justified freely by his grace through the redemption that came by Christ Jesus" (Rom 3:23-24).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "God looked down from heaven on all humanity to see if anyone understands, if anyone seeks after God." The divine omniscient survey of humanity — searching for understanding and God-seeking — and finding none is the universal negative that Paul\'s argument in Romans 1-3 establishes as the starting point of the gospel. The divine search of Ps 53:2 finds one: Christ himself, who is the only one who fully understands and fully seeks the Father (John 4:34: "my food is to do the will of him who sent me and to finish his work"). Christ is the exception to the universal finding of v2, and through union with him, the sinful are found by the God who searches.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct citation: "Every single one has turned aside; together they have become rotten; there is no one who does good — not a single person." Romans 3:12 quotes this directly. The universal apostasy — every person turned, all corrupted, none doing good — is the scriptural warrant for the universal need of grace. Without the exception that is Christ, there is no escape from this verdict. But Romans 5:18-19: "just as one trespass resulted in condemnation for all people, so also one righteous act resulted in justification and life for all people. For just as through the disobedience of the one man the many were made sinners, so also through the obedience of the one man the many will be made righteous." The "not a single one" of Psalm 53:3 is answered by the one whose obedience covers all.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme: "Don\'t those who work evil know anything — those who devour my people the way they eat bread and never call on God?" The cannibalistic metaphor for oppressors — devouring the people of God as casually as eating bread — is the OT\'s image of exploitative power. James 5:1-6 uses similar language about those who exploit their workers. The "never call on God" is the defining characteristic: the wicked have no covenantal relationship that would restrain their exploitation. Christ\'s community is constituted by calling on God (Rom 10:12-13: "everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved") — the inverse of the characterization here.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "But there they are, overwhelmed with terror where there was no terror, for God scattered the bones of those who attacked you; you put them to shame, for God rejected them." The sudden terror of the wicked who had no reason to fear — the unexpected reversal of their confidence — is the eschatological pattern. 1 Thessalonians 5:3: "while people are saying, \'Peace and safety,\' destruction will come on them suddenly, as labor pains on a pregnant woman, and they will not escape." The "scattering of bones" of those who attacked God\'s people is fulfilled eschatologically in the judgment that Christ pronounces: "Depart from me, you who are cursed" (Matt 25:41).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "Oh, that Israel\'s rescue would come out of Zion! When God restores the fortunes of his people, Jacob will rejoice and Israel will be glad." The messianic longing — the psalm closing with a cry for rescue from Zion — is the hope that Luke 2:38 describes as the expectation of Anna and others like her: "giving thanks to God and speaking about the child to all who were looking forward to the redemption of Jerusalem." Paul cites this hope in Romans 11:26 ("all Israel will be saved, as it is written: \'The deliverer will come from Zion; he will turn godlessness away from Jacob\'") — explicitly applying the Zion-rescue hope to Christ\'s future work. The "restoration of fortunes" of God\'s people is the eschatological restoration that Christ\'s return will complete.</p>',
  },
  "54": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: "To the director of music. With stringed instruments. A Maskil of David. When the Ziphites came to Saul and said, \'Is not David hiding among us?\'" The superscription situates this lament in David\'s experience of betrayal by his own countrymen (1 Sam 23:19; 26:1) — fellow Israelites who reported his location to Saul. This pattern of betrayal by those who should be loyal is the pattern of Christ\'s passion: betrayed by Judas (one of the Twelve), denied by Peter (the leading disciple), abandoned by all. The historical context of David-as-fugitive is the shadow behind which the passion narrative stands.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: "Hear my prayer, O God; listen to what I am saying." The opening petition for a hearing — the fundamental cry of the lament genre — is the prayer posture that Christ models. Hebrews 5:7: "In the days of his flesh, Jesus offered up prayers and supplications, with loud cries and tears, to him who was able to save him from death, and he was heard because of his reverence." The Gethsemane prayer (Matt 26:36-46) is the fullest instance of the "hear my prayer" of Psalm 54:2 — the cry of the righteous sufferer to the Father who hears.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme: "For outsiders are threatening me; violent men are hunting my life — people who have no thought of God." The threatening outsiders (<em>zārîm</em> — strangers/foreigners, here used of enemies) who hunt the psalmist\'s life are the hostile forces arrayed against the righteous. At Jesus\'s arrest, the crowd with swords and clubs (Mark 14:43-46), the Roman soldiers (John 18:12), and the religious authorities who plotted against him all qualify as those "hunting his life." "People who have no thought of God" — those who, in the moment of the passion, did not reckon with the divine identity of the one they were pursuing (Acts 3:17: "I know that you acted in ignorance, as did your leaders").</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "But God is my helper; the Lord is the one who sustains my life." The divine identity as helper-and-sustainer — the one who stands with the righteous sufferer when all human support fails — is the confidence of the passion narrative. Hebrews 13:6 (citing Ps 118:7): "The Lord is my helper; I will not be afraid. What can mere mortals do to me?" Christ sustained his earthly life through the Father\'s presence (John 8:29: "the one who sent me is with me; he has not left me alone"), and after the cross, the Father\'s "sustaining of life" was the resurrection — the definitive divine answer to the violence of v3.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: "He will bring the evil back on my enemies; in your faithfulness, silence them." The prayer for the return of evil upon the persecutors — covenant justice enacted — is not vindictiveness but faith in divine retribution. Romans 12:19: "do not take revenge, my dear friends, but leave room for God\'s wrath, for it is written: \'It is mine to avenge; I will repay,\' says the Lord." Christ did not call down judgment on his persecutors; instead, "Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing" (Luke 23:34). But the silencing of the wicked through divine faithfulness remains an eschatological certainty: "God will bring into judgment both the righteous and the wicked" (Eccles 3:17).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "With a generous, willing heart I will offer sacrifice to you; I will give thanks to your name, LORD, for it is good." The freewill offering (<em>nĕdāvāh</em> — the voluntary, unprompted sacrifice beyond what is required) given in thanksgiving — this is the sacrifice the NT community offers "through Jesus." 2 Corinthians 9:7: "Each of you should give what you have decided in your heart to give, not reluctantly or under compulsion, for God loves a cheerful giver." Christ himself is the archetypal freewill offering: his death was not compelled (John 10:18: "no one takes my life from me, but I lay it down of my own accord"). The generous, willing sacrifice of Ps 54:6 is the pattern Christ embodies and invites the redeemed to imitate.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "For he has rescued me from every distress, and my eye has seen the downfall of my enemies." The psalm closes with thanksgiving for comprehensive rescue — "from every distress" — and the testimony of witnessed enemy-defeat. The resurrection is the NT\'s comprehensive rescue from "every distress": death itself, the ultimate distress, has been defeated. 1 Corinthians 15:55-57: "\'Where, O death, is your victory? Where, O death, is your sting?\' The sting of death is sin, and the power of sin is the law. But thanks be to God! He gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ." The eye that "sees the downfall of enemies" is the faith that looks to the resurrection and sees death already defeated.</p>',
  },
}

